{{One source|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox artwork | image_file=Edvard Munch - Anxiety - Google Art Project.jpg | image_size=220px | title=Anxiety | other_language_1=Norwegian | other_title_1=Angst | artist=[[Edvard Munch]] | year=1894 | medium=[[Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=94.0 | width_metric=74.0 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=Oslo, Norway | museum=[[Munch Museum]] }}
'''''Anxiety''''' ({{lang-no|'''Angst'''}}) is an oil-on-canvas painting created by the [[Expressionism|expressionist]] artist [[Edvard Munch]] in 1894. It's currently housed in [[Munch Museum]] in Oslo, Norway. Many art critics{{who|date=January 2015}} feel that ''Anxiety'' is closely related to Munch’s more famous piece, ''[[The Scream]]''. The faces show despair and the dark colors show a depressed state. Many critics also believe it’s meant to show the emotions of [[Broken heart|heartbreak]] and sorrow.<ref>''[http://totallyhistory.com/anxiety/ Anxiety ]''</ref>
